165","21 October 1191":"21 October 1191","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","1228":"1228","1148":"1148","Abt 1200":"about 1200","1146":"1146","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","1189":"1189","about 1146":"about 1146","1208":"1208","Siege of Acre, Kingdom of Yerushalayim, Israel":"Yerushalayim, Jerusalem, Israel","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Suffolk Co., England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Antley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Glanville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): of Norman origin, a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, named from an ancient Germanic personal name of uncertain form and meaning + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. This name has frequently been confused with <b>Glanfield</b>, a habitational name from Glanvill Farm in Devon, Clanville in Somerset and Hampshire, or Clanfield in Hampshire, or from some other place likewise named with Old English <i>clǣne</i> ‘clean’ (i.e. free of brambles and undergrowth) + <i>feld</i> ‘pasture, open country’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Glanville was born in 1165, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ranulph de Glanville Chief Justiciar of England, was 46 and his mother, Bertha Valoines, was 36. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William de Glanville. He died in 1228, in his hometown, at the age of 63, and was buried in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1165–1228":"1165–1228","1146–1173":"1146–1173","1148–1194":"1148–1194","1162–1189":"1162–1189","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1200–1266":"1200–1266","1120–1191":"1120–1191","1130–1208":"1130–1208","1165":"1165","21 October 1191":"21. oktoober 1191","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","1228":"1228","1148":"1148","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1146":"1146","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","1189":"1189","about 1146":"umbes 1146","1208":"1208","Siege of Acre, Kingdom of Yerushalayim, Israel":"Yerushalayim, Jerusalem, Iisrael","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Suffolk Co., England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Antley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1165–1228":"1165–1228","1146–1173":"1146–1173","1148–1194":"1148–1194","1162–1189":"1162–1189","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1200–1266":"1200–1266","1120–1191":"1120–1191","1130–1208":"1130–1208","1165":"1165","21 October 1191":"21. lokakuuta 1191","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","1228":"1228","1148":"1148","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","1146":"1146","1266":"1266","1200":"1200","1189":"1189","about 1146":"noin 1146","1208":"1208","Siege of Acre, Kingdom of Yerushalayim, Israel":"Yerushalayim, Jerusalem, Israel","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Suffolk Co., England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Antley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1165–1228":"1165–1228","1146–1173":"1146–1173","1148–1194":"1148–1194","1162–1189":"1162–1189","1170–